A name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="root" value="re:china"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="seasiaz"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Southeast Asia</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="root" value="re:singp"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code></CSet><CSet fid="ns"><Code value="nedi"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Editorials</CodeD><CodeI org="rbc" action="add"><CodeA name="rule" value="837048"/><CodeA name="db" value="prbc---00018569-20180321-145544"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="ncat"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Content Types</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:nedi"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Opinion</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">EDITORIAL; For Singapore to stay on top, economic restructuring cannot rest</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>Foreign buyers accounted for over 70 per cent of the total sales value of two high-end projects, according to their developer City Developments.</Para><Para>At its New Futura project near Orchard Road, foreign buyers were mainly from China, Indonesia and Malaysia, and also included Singapore permanent residents. Over at the 174-unit Gramercy Park, also a stone's throw away from Orchard Road, the most expensive units - four penthouses - were also sold to foreigners at prices ranging from S$16.88 million to S$24.5 million.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Such confidence in Singapore's property market by foreigners may be surprising but it should not be dismissed as a one-off phenomenon. Property consultancy Knight Frank notes that there has been a significant rise in purchases by foreigners in the luxury segment in Singapore's prime areas which includes districts 9, 10 and 11, and Sentosa.</Para><Para>For the wealthy, it appears that the various stamp duties pose little deterrent.</Para><Para>Among cities around the world, Singapore is holding its own. A recent Knight Frank report saw Singapore being ranked the fifth favoured destination for property investments among the world's ultra-wealthy. It was top in Asia and among Asian investors, Singapore was the third-most sought after destination, after the US and the UK.</Para><Para>The findings were based on a City Wealth index which is based on four parameters: wealth population and its rate of growth; property investments worth at least US$10 million; lifestyle; and future economic performance.</Para><Para>What was notable was that Singapore scored particularly well on the lifestyle component, which takes into account the number of luxury hotels and leading restaurants. Other drivers include education, for example the number and quality of universities in the city.</Para><Para>This is something that Singapore excels at. Its commitment to education and ensuring a quality living environment is an achievement that has been years in the making.</Para><Para>Yet another survey out this week backs up these findings. Human resources consultant Mercer's 20th annual Quality of Living survey ranked Singapore top among Asian cities and 25th globally. Tracking 231 cities, the survey is used by multinationals looking to place their expats on overseas assignments.</Para><Para>What is also in Singapore's favour is that it is well-placed and part of a growing region. Knight Frank's Wealth Report noted that Asia has overtaken Europe in absolute numbers of the ultra-wealthy, defined as those with US$50 million or more in net assets. While North America (44,000) remains at the top spot, Asia was second (35,880), followed by Europe (35,180).</Para><Para>There is no doubt that there are trends that pose risks to Singapore's position as a successful city-state. China is no longer a low-cost manufacturing player but is moving up the value chain, protectionist threats are getting stronger, technology is a major disruptive force, the workforce is aging, and so on.</Para><Para>But these results give cause for optimism that Singapore is in a strong position, well able to maintain its competitive edge as a business city where companies locate their headquarters and individuals invest their money. But they also act as a reminder of the importance of remaining relevant in the global economy. To that end, ongoing efforts at restructuring Singapore's economy cannot rest.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">, For Singapore to stay on top, economic restructuring cannot rest </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc: